VIRGILATTE GWANGWA 
virgilatte.gwangwa@inl.co.za 
 
MEMBERS of the Fix the Patent Law Coalition marched to the Department of Transport and Industry to show their support for the government's effort to fix the country's patent law and ensure that everyone has access to the medicine they need. They said however, as much as they support the policies, they also needed new laws. “We have waited for over 10 years and all the government has given us are policies but not reforms, promise but not results,” said National chairperson of the Treatment Action Campaign. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  She said the draft IP policy was an important step but the department needed to urgently finalise the policy and publish draft bills to ensure access to medicines. “We have lost comrades because the medicine they needed was too expensive,” she said. The group of more than a hundred took to the streets of Pretoria, marching from the Pretoria Art Museum to the department raising their placards high and singing their lungs out. “The medicines are where the people are not”, “why are cancer medicines just for the rich?” and “not there yet, save our lives” were some of the messages read on the placards.